---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout 
  title="Blog — Yannik Peschke" 
  description="Articles about software architecture, microfrontends, and system design by Yannik Peschke."
>

<h1>Writing</h1>
<p class="page-intro">
  Thoughts on software architecture, microfrontends, system design, and lessons learned from building production systems.
</p>

<div class="filter-tags">
  <button class="tag active" data-filter="all">All Articles</button>
  <button class="tag" data-filter="architecture">Architecture</button>
  <button class="tag" data-filter="microfrontends">Microfrontends</button>
  <button class="tag" data-filter="system-design">System Design</button>
</div>

<div class="articles-list">
  <article class="article-card" data-tags="microfrontends,architecture">
    <div class="article-meta">January 15, 2026 · 8 min read</div>
    <h2>Module Federation in Practice: Lessons from Production</h2>
    <div class="article-tags">
      <span class="article-tag">Microfrontends</span>
      <span class="article-tag">Architecture</span>
    </div>
    <p class="article-excerpt">
      After implementing module federation across multiple teams, I've learned what works and what doesn't. 
      This article covers the patterns that emerged from real-world usage, including shared dependencies, 
      versioning strategies, and handling breaking changes in distributed systems.
    </p>
    <span class="read-more">Read article →</span>
  </article>

  <article class="article-card" data-tags="microfrontends,architecture,system-design">
    <div class="article-meta">December 28, 2025 · 12 min read</div>
    <h2>The State of Microfrontends: Architecture Patterns That Scale</h2>
    <div class="article-tags">
      <span class="article-tag">Microfrontends</span>
      <span class="article-tag">Architecture</span>
      <span class="article-tag">System Design</span>
    </div>
    <p class="article-excerpt">
      A comprehensive deep dive into microfrontend architectures. We'll compare build-time integration, 
      runtime composition, and edge-side includes, examining when each approach makes sense. Includes 
      real-world performance data and team organization considerations.
    </p>
    <span class="read-more">Read article →</span>
  </article>

  <article class="article-card" data-tags="system-design,architecture">
    <div class="article-meta">November 20, 2025 · 6 min read</div>
    <h2>System Design Principles: Composability Over Complexity</h2>
    <div class="article-tags">
      <span class="article-tag">System Design</span>
      <span class="article-tag">Architecture</span>
    </div>
    <p class="article-excerpt">
      Why breaking systems into composable pieces leads to more maintainable architectures. This article 
      explores how to identify the right boundaries, balance coupling and cohesion, and design systems 
      that can evolve without complete rewrites.
    </p>
    <span class="read-more">Read article →</span>
  </article>

  <article class="article-card" data-tags="architecture">
    <div class="article-meta">October 12, 2025 · 10 min read</div>
    <h2>Frontend Architecture: Beyond Components</h2>
    <div class="article-tags">
      <span class="article-tag">Architecture</span>
    </div>
    <p class="article-excerpt">
      Component libraries are just the beginning. This article discusses state management strategies, 
      data fetching patterns, error boundaries, and how to structure frontend applications for long-term 
      maintainability. Focus on practical patterns rather than framework-specific solutions.
    </p>
    <span class="read-more">Read article →</span>
  </article>

  <article class="article-card" data-tags="microfrontends,system-design">
    <div class="article-meta">September 5, 2025 · 9 min read</div>
    <h2>Shared State in Microfrontends: Patterns and Pitfalls</h2>
    <div class="article-tags">
      <span class="article-tag">Microfrontends</span>
      <span class="article-tag">System Design</span>
    </div>
    <p class="article-excerpt">
      Managing shared state across independently deployed microfrontends is challenging. We'll explore 
      different approaches: custom events, shared stores, URL-based state, and when to use each. 
      Includes code examples and performance considerations.
    </p>
    <span class="read-more">Read article →</span>
  </article>

  <article class="article-card" data-tags="architecture,system-design">
    <div class="article-meta">August 18, 2025 · 7 min read</div>
    <h2>API Design: Making Breaking Changes Without Breaking Things</h2>
    <div class="article-tags">
      <span class="article-tag">Architecture</span>
      <span class="article-tag">System Design</span>
    </div>
    <p class="article-excerpt">
      How to evolve APIs in production without breaking existing clients. Covers versioning strategies, 
      deprecation patterns, and techniques for graceful migrations. Real examples from managing APIs 
      across multiple teams and services.
    </p>
    <span class="read-more">Read article →</span>
  </article>

  <article class="article-card" data-tags="system-design">
    <div class="article-meta">July 22, 2025 · 11 min read</div>
    <h2>Building for Scale: Lessons from Growing Systems</h2>
    <div class="article-tags">
      <span class="article-tag">System Design</span>
    </div>
    <p class="article-excerpt">
      What happens when your system needs to handle 10x the traffic? This article shares lessons learned 
      from scaling web applications, including caching strategies, database optimization, and identifying 
      bottlenecks before they become problems.
    </p>
    <span class="read-more">Read article →</span>
  </article>

  <article class="article-card" data-tags="architecture">
    <div class="article-meta">June 14, 2025 · 5 min read</div>
    <h2>The Cost of Abstraction: When to Abstract and When to Repeat</h2>
    <div class="article-tags">
      <span class="article-tag">Architecture</span>
    </div>
    <p class="article-excerpt">
      Not every duplication needs an abstraction. This short article discusses the trade-offs between 
      DRY principles and premature abstraction, and how to decide when it's worth creating shared code 
      versus accepting some repetition.
    </p>
    <span class="read-more">Read article →</span>
  </article>
</div>

</Layout>

<style>
.page-intro {
  font-size: 1.125rem;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  margin-bottom: var(--spacing-xl);
}

.filter-tags {
  display: flex;
  gap: var(--spacing-sm);
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  margin-bottom: var(--spacing-lg);
  font-family: var(--font-main);
}

.tag {
  padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
  font-size: 12px;
  background-color: transparent;
  border: 1px dashed var(--border-color);
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: all 0.2s ease;
  font-family: var(--font-main);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  font-weight: 700;
}

.tag:hover, .tag.active {
  background-color: transparent;
  color: var(--accent);
  border-color: var(--accent);
  border-style: solid;
  text-shadow: 0 0 5px rgba(192, 254, 4, 0.4);
}

.tag.active::before {
  content: "[x] ";
}

.tag:not(.active)::before {
  content: "[ ] ";
}

.articles-list {
  display: grid;
  gap: var(--spacing-md);
}

.article-card {
  text-decoration: none;
  color: inherit;
  display: block;
  padding: var(--spacing-md);
  padding-left: var(--spacing-lg);
  border-left: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  background: transparent;
  transition: all 0.2s ease;
  position: relative;
}

.article-card:hover {
  border-left-color: var(--accent);
  padding-left: calc(var(--spacing-lg) + 10px);
}

.article-card:last-child {
  border-left: 1px solid var(--border-color);
}

.article-card:last-child:hover {
  border-left-color: var(--accent);
}

.article-meta {
  font-family: var(--font-main);
  font-size: 12px;
  color: var(--text-tertiary);
  margin-bottom: var(--spacing-xs);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.05em;
}

.article-card h2 {
  font-size: 1.75rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  margin-bottom: var(--spacing-xs);
  letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  transition: color 0.2s ease;
  color: var(--text-primary);
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
}

.article-card h2::before {
  content: ">";
  margin-right: 10px;
  color: var(--accent);
  opacity: 0;
  transform: translateX(-10px);
  transition: all 0.2s ease;
}

.article-card:hover h2::before {
  opacity: 1;
  transform: translateX(0);
}

.article-card:hover h2 {
  color: var(--accent);
}

.article-tags {
  display: flex;
  gap: var(--spacing-xs);
  margin-bottom: var(--spacing-sm);
}

.article-tag {
  font-family: var(--font-main);
  font-size: 11px;
  padding: 0.25rem 0.5rem;
  background-color: transparent;
  color: var(--text-tertiary);
  border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  text-transform: uppercase;
}

.article-excerpt {
  font-size: 1rem;
  color: var(--text-secondary);
  line-height: 1.6;
}

.read-more {
  font-family: var(--font-main);
  font-size: 13px;
  color: var(--accent);
  margin-top: var(--spacing-sm);
  display: inline-block;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  font-weight: 700;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  h1 {
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-sm);
  }
}
</style>

<script>
  // Filter functionality
  const filterTags = document.querySelectorAll('.tag');
  const articles = document.querySelectorAll('.article-card');

  filterTags.forEach(tag => {
    tag.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const filter = tag.getAttribute('data-filter');
      
      filterTags.forEach(t => t.classList.remove('active'));
      tag.classList.add('active');

      articles.forEach(article => {
        const tags = article.getAttribute('data-tags');
        
        if (filter === 'all' || tags.includes(filter)) {
          article.style.display = 'block';
        } else {
          article.style.display = 'none';
        }
      });
    });
  });
</script>
